Transmission and capture data were analyzed for
resonance parameters using R-matrix Bayesian code
SAMMY. The analysis employed the experimental
features of SAMMY. Both capture and transmission yield
data were fitted and final set of parameters was
Data taken from tab.4 of the reference
The SAMMY-fit Bayesian resonance parameters determined
in this work (Table IV) and ENDF parameters for
resonances above 600 eV (including p-waves) were input
to the NJOY nuclear data processing code35 to obtain
Doppler-broadened cross sections and the thermal
Uncertainties of thermal cross section were
determined via a Monte Carlo method where the fitted
resonance parameters were sampled from Gaussian
distributions centered on the fitted resonance
parameter values with standard deviations equal to the
uncertainty of the fitted values. The thermal cross
section was computed with each set of sampled resonance
parameters. The mean values of the calculations were
taken to be the thermal cross section, and the standard
deviations of the calculation results were taken to be
Data taken from tab.5 of the reference
Resonance integral was determined from calculated
cross sections by simple integration utilizing the
Uncertainties of the resonance integral were
determined via a Monte Carlo method where the fitted
resonance parameters were sampled from Gaussian
distributions centered on the fitted resonance
parameter values with standard deviations equal to the
uncertainty of the fitted values. The resonance
integral was computed with each set of sampled
resonance parameters. The mean values of the
calculations were taken to be the resonance integral,
and the standard deviations of the calculation results
were taken to be the uncertainties on these values.
